sql:
SELECT p.predicted_insurance_rate
FROM predictions p
WHERE p.czone = 0;

external_knowledge:
- "80% of the population insured" refers to a high level of health insurance coverage, indicating that the majority of the population has access to healthcare services;
- "10% participation in Medicaid" refers to a significant portion of the population relying on government-funded health insurance, often due to low income or other qualifying factors;
- "Demographic and health metrics" include factors such as the fraction of the population that is Black or Hispanic, educational attainment, poverty rate, hospital occupancy, average length of stay, and prevalence of physical disabilities, obesity, and smoking, which provide a comprehensive view of the health and socio-economic conditions of the population in each hospital zone.

sql:
SELECT AVG(predicted_health_metric) AS average_health_metric
FROM predictions
WHERE czone = 0;

SELECT czone, predicted_insurance_rate
FROM predictions
WHERE predicted_insurance_rate > 0.8;

SELECT czone, predicted_hospitalizations
FROM predictions
ORDER BY predicted_hospitalizations DESC;

external_knowledge:
- "hospital type" includes categories such as public, private, and non-profit;
- "average bed capacity" is the mean number of hospital beds available across all zones of the same hospital type;
- "spacious wings" refers to the hospital type with the highest average number of hospital beds.

- Hospital zones are regions where hospitals are located, and they can vary in terms of community financial health and hospital occupancy;
- Financial health is measured by median house value, total income, and the fraction of the population that is poor;
- Hospital occupancy is the rate at which hospital beds are occupied.

- "Insurance rate" refers to the fraction of patients with insurance;
- "Hospital bed availability" is the total number of hospital beds across all zones;
- "Occupancy rate" is the highest percentage of hospital beds occupied in any zone;
- "Charity payments" are the minimum total amounts paid by charity for patients;
- "Demographic metrics" include the average fractions of the population that are Black, Hispanic, have more than a high school education, and are poor;
- "Health metrics" include the average rates of physical disabilities, obesity, and smoking.

- "Occupancy rate greater than 0.5" means the hospital has more than 50% of its beds occupied;
- "Average number of doctors" is calculated by averaging the number of doctors per hospital zone;
- "Fraction of the population" refers to the percentage of the population within a specific demographic category.

- "Above-average occupancy rate" refers to a rate higher than the average occupancy rate across all hospital zones;
- "Significant Black and Hispanic population" refers to a fraction of the population that is Black greater than 0.2 and a fraction of the population that is Hispanic greater than 0.1;
- "High level of education" refers to a fraction of the population with educational attainment greater than high school greater than 0.6.
